[EHD is fairly widespread in the USA. These reports are relatively common in the hot summer, especially late summer and fall prior to a frost.

EHD is the most important disease of white-tailed deer. Outbreaks are common in the Southeast of USA, but they are also frequently documented further North. The disease is transmitted by biting midges and its occurrence is seasonal, from late summer to early fall. The die-offs cease with the 1st frosts. The EHD virus does not pose a risk for human or livestock health.

High density deer herds may have higher mortality rates; however, the relationship of deer density to the severity of hemorrhagic disease is not clear-cut, as the virus is not spread by direct contact and depends on the dynamics of the arthropod vector. For more information on the disease see comments on ProMED-mail post 20110918.2842.

Delaware may be found on the interactive Healthmap at: http://healthmap.org/r/3aMn.

The original website for this article has a reasonable picture of a white tail doe. - Mod.TG]
